        allStories.add(new Story("Marvel Cinematic Universe (Abridged)", "DungeonMistress", "Marvel Cinematic Universe", "After the events of Endgame...", "Action, Drama", "Comedy", "So Tony Stark is in the back of a military convoy getting absolutely plastered, flirting with the driver, taking pictures and reminding himself to buy Myspace before it becomes irrelevant in like...3 hours. But suddenly all of the shit hits several fans and the van he's in becomes target practice. He tries to escape and order a quick pizza or something but he soon finds the bad guys have a missile with his name on it.\nLiterally.\nWhen he wakes up, he realizes the guys that decided to send his weapons back the fun way, are kind of assholes. So he decides to ignore them and take a nap so good it blasts him a few days back, where he could be winning an award but nah, he's gonna play craps. Stark is like \"Ah just give Ceaser the award. He deserves some thanks for that awesome salad I had earlier.\" He meets some reporter chick who asks him why he's the head of a weapons development company that makes weapons to sell to the military despite it being a family tradition. But to be fair, who actually expects reporters to do research and rational thinking? So to get her to shut up for five seconds and let him talk about how it's better then painting, Stark takes the reporter home and performs the classic Hump and Dump. His assistant Pepper then proceeds to throw the reporter's half naked ass out the door, most likely expecting her to walk back to Vegas from Malibu.\nStark tries holding off on going to the weapons show he's holding, but he's read the script already so he figures he might as well go, but he'll be damned if he's not gonna get some drunk lap dances in before he arrives. He goes, does the show, tells his oddly sinister partner to put some pajamas on, gets captured but we've already seen this part.\nRealizing that a missile to the heart fucking hurts, Stark and some bald guy named Yensin build a tiny blue light and force it into Stark's chest. The leader of the bad guys says he wants a new missile. Apparently the one that almost killed Stark was his favorite but now he can't play with it anymore, so he wants a better one.\nStark says \"Lol fuck you\" and builds a suit instead, killing absolutely everyone and blowing up everything in the terrorists base. Yensin dies or whatever but to be fair, it was he wanted. Living in the same cave as Stark for a week will do that to a guy.\nWhen Stark is done playing hostage he goes home, gets a cheesburger, shuts down his company's weapons project and now everyone is mad at him. And that children is why you don't cave when the Media tells you what is what.\nAfter telling Pepper to put her fingers in his gaping wet hole, Stark sits in his basement for a while, thinking \"hey that suit thing was kinda fun. I wanna do it again. And i'm gonna go to the FUCKING MOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOON!\" Turns out space is pretty cold. He gives his suit a paint job and goes partying with Disney for a while, hearing rumors they wanted in on the Stark company name. He runs into a familiar looking old guy that he could swear he's seen somewhere before, dances with Pepper for a bit, goes to get her a drink, but right in the middle of realizing he's not the kind of guy to commit, he's just about to skip the Hump and go straight to the Dump, the reporter bitch comes in, saying Stark lied about planning to stop selling weapons. Once again, no research was done, and it turns out the oddly sinister partner from earlier Obidiah Stane is an asshole. And he's manged to build his own suit.\nStark flies over to where the new weapons are showing up, an tells the bad guys: I told yall guys no weapons. Bad. Bad bad guys. Go to your room.\n\"Lol fuck you\" They say in response as they shoot him with a tank. Stark laughs and says \"no u\" and shoots their tank with himself. He comes home in time for Pepper to see he's been out having fun in his new suit, and she tries to leave, but he calls her out on running away from a man trying to fix his mistakes, and she remembers when she put herself past the wrist into this mans gaping hole and decided to help prove that Stane is shady as fuck. \nStane finds out about this, finishes building his own suit, and then paralyzes Tony with some Rickroll. He takes out that big glowy light in Stark's chest and uses it as a way to power his own suit. Luckily every Tony Stark takes AA batteries to work properly, and so he gets in his own suit and both him and Stane try to kill each other, and Tony tells Pepper to blow up the roof they're fighting on and she's like \"But you'll die\" \nAnd Tony's like \"Do it! I got Plot Armor! My contract specified two sequels and potential crossovers!\" And so Pepper does it, and then Tony wakes up like an hour later, Stane is dead, there's a building that needs repairs and his government issued cover story is just as stupid as it was back in the 70s. So in front of the media demanding an explanation, he gives them the one thing they can't twist into a lie and don't need to research because it's only three words.\n I am Iron Man."));
        allStories.add(new Story("Five Minutes to Impact", "AvengersFan129", "Marvel Cinematic Universe", "A random morning for the avengers...", "Action, Battle, Avengers Team Dynamics", "Action", "The alarm blared across the Avengers Compound just after midnight. Tony Stark was the first to speak. “Alright, which one of you geniuses broke the world this time?” Natasha Romanoff didn’t look up from the holographic display hovering over the table. “Not broken yet,” she said calmly. “But it will be in about five minutes.” The projection rotated, revealing a glowing object screaming toward Earth. Steve Rogers folded his arms. “Meteor?” Tony tilted his head and zoomed in. “Not a meteor. Way too controlled.” The image sharpened, showing metal plating, thrusters, and weapon ports along the surface. Clint Barton whistled softly from the corner. “That’s a ship.” Bruce Banner frowned at the display. “And it’s not slowing down.” Thor stepped forward, lightning faintly crackling along the edges of his armor. “Then we meet it in the sky.” Tony snapped his helmet shut with a grin. “Finally. Someone speaking my language.”\nThirty seconds later the Avengers were airborne. Iron Man and Thor reached the object first as the ship burned through the upper atmosphere, glowing red from the heat of reentry. Tony circled it carefully. “Yeah, that’s definitely not friendly.” A panel on the side of the ship suddenly slid open and a row of energy cannons powered up. “Called it,” Tony muttered. The first blast shot past him and detonated in the clouds behind him. Thor raised Mjolnir and hurled it forward, smashing into the ship’s hull with a thunderclap that rippled through the sky. “Nice entrance, Point Break,” Tony said. The strike cracked part of the hull, but the ship continued falling toward Earth without slowing.\nBack on the ground, Steve rode inside a Quinjet with Natasha, Clint, and Bruce. “Tony, what are we looking at?” Steve asked through the comms. “Big alien delivery system,” Tony replied. “And based on the weapons, they didn’t come to drop off cookies.” Natasha checked the incoming data. “Impact point?” Tony hesitated for a moment before answering. “…New York.” Clint groaned from the back of the jet. “Again?”\nThor slammed against the ship’s side and ripped open part of a glowing panel. Sparks sprayed across the sky as systems inside the craft flickered. Suddenly, alien drones began pouring out of the opening. Tony sighed over the comms. “Okay, yeah, that tracks.” He fired a barrage of repulsor blasts that knocked several drones out of the air while Thor spun Mjolnir, sending arcs of lightning tearing through the swarm. Despite the assault, the massive ship continued its descent toward the planet. “Little busy up here!” Tony said. “Any ideas?”\nInside the Quinjet, Bruce looked up slowly. Steve raised an eyebrow. “Bruce?” Bruce exhaled. “Guess it’s that kind of night.” The Quinjet’s rear ramp opened high above the ocean. Bruce stepped forward and jumped. For a few seconds there was only silence on the comms. Then Hulk smashed directly into the falling ship. The impact dented the hull like a crushed soda can. Systems inside the craft immediately began to fail as the thrusters sputtered and died. The ship started to spin violently in the air. Tony blinked at the sight. “Well… that worked.” Thor laughed as lightning destroyed the last remaining drones. The crippled ship veered off course and crashed into the Atlantic Ocean with a massive explosion of steam and water.\nLater, back at the compound, the team gathered around the table again as if the entire event had been nothing more than a routine drill. Clint tossed an apple lazily in the air. “So… does that count as a successful mission?” Tony leaned back in his chair. “Planet’s still here. I’m counting it.” Thor grinned proudly. “A glorious battle!” Bruce rubbed the back of his neck awkwardly. “Sorry about the dent in the ship.” Natasha smirked. “Pretty sure that was the point.” Steve looked around the room at the team—five minutes from disaster, and somehow they had handled it the way they always did. He allowed himself a small smile. “Good work, Avengers.”"));

        // Harry Potter section
        allStories.add(new Story("Wands and Wizards", "MagicStudent", "Harry Potter", "A new year at Hogwarts begins.", "Hogwarts, Slow Burn, Magical Moments", "Romance","The courtyard at Hogwarts was quiet in the early evening, the kind of calm that only came after the last class of the day when most students had already disappeared toward dinner. The golden light of sunset spilled across the stone walls and long shadows stretched over the grass. Elena sat on the low edge of the fountain, her wand resting loosely in her hand as she practiced small levitation charms. A fallen leaf hovered uncertainly in the air before wobbling and dropping back onto the ground. She sighed and brushed a strand of hair out of her face.\n“Still fighting with Wingardium Leviosa, I see.”\nShe turned to find Adrian leaning casually against one of the courtyard pillars, arms crossed and a familiar amused smile on his face. Elena narrowed her eyes. “I’m not fighting with it. I’m refining it.” Adrian chuckled softly and stepped closer. “That leaf has been ‘refining’ itself for about ten minutes.” He drew his wand with a lazy flick and lifted the same leaf effortlessly into the air. It floated smoothly between them before drifting back down. Elena groaned. “You’re insufferable, you know that?” “And yet,” Adrian said with a grin, “you keep practicing out here where you know I’ll find you.”\nShe opened her mouth to argue but stopped when she realized he wasn’t entirely wrong. Ever since third year they’d somehow ended up in the same quiet corners of the castle after classes—sometimes to study, sometimes to argue about spells, and sometimes just to sit there in comfortable silence. Elena tapped her wand against the stone fountain and tried the spell again. This time the leaf rose slowly, wobbling at first before steadying itself in the air. Adrian raised an eyebrow, clearly impressed. “Alright, I’ll admit it,” he said. “That was better.”\nElena smirked and let the leaf drift down again. “See? Refining.” For a moment neither of them spoke. The courtyard lights flickered on one by one, casting a warm glow across the ancient stone. Somewhere in the distance, laughter echoed from the castle halls. Adrian leaned back against the fountain beside her, close enough that their shoulders nearly touched. “You know,” he said quietly, “most people would just ask for help instead of struggling with a spell for ten minutes.”\n“And miss the chance to prove you wrong?” Elena replied. “Never.”\nAdrian laughed softly. Then he lifted his wand again, pointing it toward the fountain. A small swirl of golden sparks rose into the air, forming the shape of a glowing bird that fluttered lazily above the water before dissolving into glittering light. Elena watched it disappear, surprised. “That’s not in the standard charms textbook,” she said. “No,” Adrian admitted. “I made it up.” He glanced at her, suddenly looking a little less confident than usual. “Figured it might be useful someday.”\nElena looked at him curiously. “Useful for what?”\nAdrian hesitated for a second before answering. “For getting someone’s attention.”\nFor once, Elena had no clever reply. The evening breeze stirred the trees around the courtyard, sending a few leaves drifting across the stones. She raised her wand again and flicked it lightly. This time the leaves rose together, floating gently around them in a slow orbit. Adrian blinked in surprise. “Alright,” he said quietly, watching the spell hold steady. “That’s definitely better.”\nElena smiled, feeling the warmth creep into her cheeks. “Guess I learn quickly.”\nThe leaves slowly settled back onto the ground as the spell faded. For a moment the courtyard was quiet again, lit only by the soft glow of the lamps and the distant windows of Hogwarts. Adrian glanced at her and smiled in a way that was softer than usual. “Same time tomorrow?” he asked.\nElena twirled her wand between her fingers, pretending to consider it. Then she stood up from the fountain. “Maybe,” she said lightly, already walking toward the castle. Adrian followed a few steps behind, still smiling. And somewhere above them, hidden among the towers of Hogwarts, another quiet evening had just become a little more magical."));
        allStories.add(new Story("The Duel Beneath the Clocktower", "Voldemort_Wins", "Harry Potter", "Hogwarts Duel, who will win??", "Wands, Harry Potter, Magic", "Fantasy", "The halls of Hogwarts were quiet long after curfew, lit only by the wavering glow of floating candles. Wind rattled the tall windows near the old clocktower as Harry Potter hurried down the corridor, wand raised. He had received a strange message only minutes earlier—three hurried words scribbled on a scrap of parchment: Clocktower. Come alone. Waiting in the shadows was Draco Malfoy, pale and tense, his wand already drawn. For a moment neither spoke, the distant ticking of the giant clock echoing around them like a countdown.\n“You shouldn’t have come,” Draco said quietly. Harry frowned. “You sent the message.” Draco hesitated, glancing toward the staircase behind him. “I didn’t send it.” Before Harry could respond, the torches suddenly flickered out and a cold laugh drifted through the hall. From the darkness stepped a masked wizard, robes marked with the twisted symbol of a Death Eaters supporter. “How convenient,” the stranger sneered. “The Boy Who Lived… and the Malfoy heir. The Dark Lord will be pleased.”\nBoth boys reacted instantly. “Expelliarmus!” Harry shouted, his spell colliding with Draco’s own curse in a burst of sparks that forced the attacker backward. The masked wizard retaliated with a crack of green light that blasted apart a stone railing, sending debris crashing down the stairs. Harry ducked behind a pillar while Draco fired a rapid string of jinxes that filled the corridor with flashes of red and gold. The clock above them thundered loudly, each swing of the pendulum echoing through the duel.\nFinally Harry saw an opening. As the wizard raised his wand again, Harry stepped forward and cast with everything he had. “Stupefy!” The spell struck squarely, knocking the attacker flat against the stone floor. Silence returned to the clocktower except for the slow, steady ticking overhead. Draco lowered his wand first, glancing uneasily at Harry. “Don’t get used to working together,” he muttered before turning away. Harry watched him disappear down the corridor, the strange alliance lingering in the air like the fading glow of magic."));

        // Star Wars Section
        allStories.add(new Story("Echoes of the Force", "DarthVader69", "Star Wars", "Something is changing in the galaxy.", "Aliens, Space, Exploration", "Sci-Fi", "The desert wind howled across the broken ruins of an ancient outpost on the outer rim. Sand swept through the shattered archways, whispering through the empty halls like distant voices. Jedi Knight Kael Varyn stepped cautiously across the cracked stone floor, his robe shifting in the wind. Something about the place felt wrong. The Force itself seemed restless here, like water disturbed by an unseen ripple.\nBehind him, his apprentice Mira struggled to keep up, shielding her eyes from the blowing sand. “Master,” she said nervously, “are you sure this is where the signal came from?” Kael nodded slowly, his gaze fixed on the dark corridor ahead. “Yes. The Republic beacon went silent here three days ago.” He paused, reaching out through the Force. Beneath the sound of the wind, he felt something else—cold, sharp, and watching. “We’re not alone.”\nBefore Mira could respond, a red blade ignited in the darkness.\nThe glow of a lightsaber spilled into the ruined hall as a cloaked figure stepped forward. The humming weapon cast crimson light across the cracked walls. Mira instinctively ignited her own saber, the blue blade flaring to life with a snap-hiss. Kael raised his hand slightly, signaling her to hold steady. The stranger tilted their head slightly, studying them through the shadow of their hood.\n“A Jedi,” the figure said calmly. “I wondered who the Republic would send.”\nKael stepped forward, his own green lightsaber igniting with a quiet hum. “Stand down,” he said firmly. “This outpost belongs to the Republic.”\nThe cloaked figure laughed softly. “Not anymore.” In an instant, the Sith lunged.\nTheir blade clashed against Kael’s with a violent burst of sparks, the impact echoing through the empty ruins. Mira moved quickly, circling the fight as Kael parried a rapid series of strikes. The Sith was fast—faster than most opponents Kael had faced—and their attacks came with precise, relentless force. Stone shattered as a stray blow slammed into one of the old pillars, sending dust raining down.\nMira waited for the opening Kael had taught her to watch for. When the Sith spun for another strike, she stepped forward and intercepted the attack. Blue and red blades collided, casting flickering light across the walls. The Sith staggered slightly, surprised, but quickly regained their footing. With a sharp motion of their hand, a wave of Force energy blasted Mira backward across the room.\n“Mira!” Kael shouted.\nShe slammed into a broken wall, gasping as she struggled to stand. Across the room, the Sith raised their saber again, ready to strike down the Jedi Knight. But Kael had already moved. Drawing on the Force, he leapt forward, bringing his blade down in a powerful arc. The clash of sabers rang like thunder through the ruins. The Sith’s stance faltered for just a moment.\nIt was enough.\nWith a swift movement, Kael disarmed the attacker, sending the red lightsaber spinning across the stone floor. The cloaked figure stumbled back, their hood falling slightly as they realized the fight was lost. For a long moment, the three of them stood in silence while the desert wind roared through the broken halls.\nThe Sith slowly raised their hands in surrender. Kael deactivated his blade but kept it ready at his side. Mira stepped forward beside him, still catching her breath but holding her lightsaber steady.\n“Remember this,” the Sith said quietly, their voice calm despite defeat. “The Force is shifting. The galaxy will not remain at peace for long.”\nKael studied the figure carefully before responding. “The Force will always find balance.”\nOutside, the wind continued to sweep across the desert ruins as the twin lightsabers faded from glowing blades back into silence. Far above the barren world, the stars burned quietly in the endless sky, unaware that another small battle between light and dark had just come to an end."));
        allStories.add(new Story("Star Wars: Starlight Over Taris", "Luke_Skywalker", "Star Wars", "An adventure through space and unexpected ambush.", "Sci-Fi, Space", "Sci-Fi", "The stars above Taris shimmered like scattered diamonds against the blackness of space. From the cockpit of the small freighter Wayward Comet, Captain Lira Dane leaned back in her seat and stretched her arms. The ship drifted quietly in orbit, its engines humming softly as the planet slowly rotated beneath them. “Remind me again,” she muttered, glancing over her shoulder, “why we agreed to help a Jedi?”\nFrom the navigation console behind her, the young Jedi Padawan Corin looked up from a datapad. “Because the Republic is paying you,” he said politely. Lira snorted and shook her head. “Yeah, but that’s usually not enough of a reason.” Across the cockpit, the ship’s mechanic Drox—an enormous, broad-shouldered alien with grease-stained hands—laughed as he tightened a bolt on a half-open panel. “You say that every time we take a job.” Lira leaned forward and rested her chin on her hand. “That’s because every time the job turns into a disaster.”\nCorin opened his mouth to reply, but suddenly the console alarms blared. Three red blips appeared on the radar screen. Lira sat upright instantly. “Well,” she said dryly, “speak of the Sith.” Three sleek starfighters dropped out of hyperspace directly behind them. Imperial. The cockpit filled with warning lights as the fighters accelerated toward the freighter. “Tell me those are friendly,” Drox said hopefully. “Do they look friendly?” Lira shot back as she grabbed the controls.\nThe Wayward Comet roared to life as she slammed the throttle forward. The ship surged away from the planet’s orbit just as green laser fire streaked past the cockpit window. Corin gripped the seat beside him. “Why would the Empire be here?” Lira pulled the freighter into a sharp roll to avoid another blast. “Kid,” she said, “if the Empire is chasing you, that’s usually the part you explain before we leave the spaceport.”\nThe Imperial fighters spread out behind them like hunting birds. “Drox!” Lira shouted. “Get the turret online!” The mechanic slammed the panel closed and sprinted toward the rear gun station. A second later the ship’s turret roared to life, firing bright red bolts back toward their pursuers. One of the starfighters veered aside as the shots flashed past its wing. “Almost had him!” Drox shouted over the comm. “Almost doesn’t count!” Lira replied as another laser blast rocked the ship and sent sparks flying from the control panel.\nCorin steadied himself and closed his eyes briefly. Through the chaos, he reached out with the Force. The presence of the three pilots flickered in his mind—sharp, focused, aggressive. Then he felt something else: an opening. “Captain,” Corin said suddenly, “turn left—now!” Lira didn’t hesitate. She jerked the controls sideways just as two of the starfighters collided with each other while trying to follow the maneuver. The explosion lit up the stars behind them. Drox whooped from the turret. “Hey! The kid’s good!”\n“One more on our tail,” Lira said, checking the radar. The final fighter surged forward, lining up a shot at the freighter’s engines. Corin took a slow breath and reached into the Force again. “Wait for it…” he murmured. The Imperial pilot fired. “Now!” Corin shouted.\nLira yanked the ship upward while Drox fired the turret straight ahead. The two blasts crossed paths in the darkness and slammed directly into the fighter as it flew through the line of fire. The starfighter erupted into a burst of light that briefly illuminated the cockpit. Then silence fell over the comms as the stars returned to their quiet stillness.\nLira slowly eased the ship back into a steady course. “Alright,” she said after a moment. “New rule.” Drox leaned into the cockpit doorway. “What rule?” Lira glanced at Corin, who looked slightly embarrassed but pleased. “Next time,” she said, “we bring the Jedi on every job.”\nOutside the freighter’s window, the stars stretched endlessly across the galaxy as the Wayward Comet jumped into hyperspace, vanishing into a streak of blue light."));
        allStories.add(new Story("Thirty Seconds of The Force", "Anakin67420", "Star Wars", "Aminosity in the force", "Action, Space", "Action", "The freighter Wayfarer dropped out of hyperspace into a quiet stretch of stars, its engines groaning as they cooled. In the cockpit, Luke Skywalker leaned toward the sensor display. “Three fighters,” he said calmly. Han Solo spun around in his chair. “You say that way too calmly,” he muttered. Outside the viewport, three screaming TIE Fighters burst into view, their laser cannons already firing. The ship shuddered as red bolts struck the shields, and Chewbacca stormed into the cockpit with an angry roar. Han frantically flipped switches at the controls. “Kid, unless you’ve got a miracle planned, we’re about to become space dust!”\nLuke closed his eyes for a brief moment, letting the chaos fade as he reached out through the Force. When he opened them again, they were calm and focused. “Buy me thirty seconds,” he said, igniting his lightsaber with a sharp snap-hiss. The green blade illuminated the cockpit as he climbed into the turret hatch above them. Han stared after him in disbelief. “Thirty seconds for what?” he shouted, but Luke was already gone.\nThe first fighter swooped in, lasers blazing. Luke steadied himself in the turret chamber, sensing the movement before it happened. The instant a bolt screamed toward the ship, his blade flashed. The laser ricocheted off the lightsaber and streaked back through space, striking the fighter’s wing and sending it spinning into a fiery explosion. “WHAT?!” Han yelled from below. The remaining fighters dove in together, filling the stars with crimson fire, but Luke’s blade moved faster—deflecting shot after shot until one blast clipped a cockpit and the damaged fighter smashed into its wingmate. Both ships erupted in a silent burst of light.\nMoments later Luke climbed back down, deactivating the saber. Han slowly turned toward him, eyes wide. “I’m just gonna say,” he muttered, “that was all part of my brilliant flying.” Chewbacca gave a rumbling laugh while Luke simply smiled out at the quiet starfield. “Let’s get back to the Rebellion,” he said. Han pulled the hyperspace lever, and the Wayfarer leapt forward, vanishing into streaking blue light as the galaxy swallowed them once more."));

        // Supernatural Section
        allStories.add(new Story("The Last Train Home", "ISwearISawSlender", "Supernatural", "A scary Slender Man encounter...", "Ghosts, Haunting", "Horror", "The train station was almost empty by the time Daniel arrived. The fluorescent lights flickered softly above the platform, casting pale reflections across the polished floor. A digital sign above the tracks read 11:58 PM, counting down the minutes until the last train of the night. Daniel adjusted the strap of his bag and glanced around the quiet station. A few scattered passengers sat on benches nearby, each lost in their own world.\nWhen the train finally arrived, it slid into the station with a low mechanical hiss. The doors opened slowly, revealing rows of nearly empty seats inside. Daniel stepped aboard and sat near the window. The train lurched forward a moment later, pulling away from the station and disappearing into the dark tunnels beneath the city.\nFor the first few stops, everything felt normal. A few passengers boarded, a few stepped off. The quiet hum of the train filled the space between stations. Daniel leaned his head against the window, watching the dark blur of the tunnel pass by outside. Then the train stopped at a station Daniel had never seen before.\nThe doors slid open with their usual soft chime, but no one stepped on or off. The platform outside was strangely dim, the station name on the wall barely visible beneath layers of peeling paint. Daniel frowned and leaned forward slightly to read it.\nThe sign said Riverside.\nThat didn’t make sense. Riverside Station had been closed for years.\nDaniel glanced around the train, expecting someone else to notice. But the other passengers remained completely silent. A man in a gray coat stared blankly at the floor. A woman near the door sat perfectly still, her hands folded in her lap. None of them looked up.\nThe doors closed again.\nThe train continued moving.\nA few minutes later, the intercom crackled overhead.\n“Next stop,” the voice said. But instead of a station name, there was only static.\nDaniel shifted uneasily in his seat. Something about the car felt different now. Quieter than before. He looked around again, this time studying the other passengers more carefully. The man in the gray coat still hadn’t moved. Neither had the woman by the door.\nIn fact, Daniel realized slowly, none of them had moved at all since Riverside.\nThe train began to slow again.\nThe doors slid open at the next station.\nDaniel immediately recognized the name this time.\nOakridge.\nHis stomach tightened.\nOakridge was the station where his old neighborhood used to be—before the fire ten years ago.\nHe looked around again, his pulse beginning to race. The passengers were still sitting exactly the same way. The train doors waited open, the platform outside silent and empty. Then the woman by the door slowly turned her head. Her eyes met Daniel's. For the first time since he boarded the train, someone acknowledged him.\nShe gave him a small, patient smile.\n“You’re not supposed to be here,” she said quietly.\nDaniel stared at her. “What do you mean?”\nThe woman glanced toward the open doors and then back at him.\n“This train,” she said softly, “only stops for people who never made it home.”\nDaniel felt the blood drain from his face.\nThe train doors began to close.\n“Wait!” he shouted, jumping to his feet.\nThe woman watched him calmly as the train started moving again. Daniel ran toward the door and looked back at the platform as it slipped away into the darkness of the tunnel.\nBehind him, the passengers still hadn’t moved. And over the intercom, the static slowly returned.\n“Final stop,” the voice whispered."));

